## Key Characteristics / Features  
### Hardware Architecture  
#### Transistors and Integrated Circuits  
The hallmark of this generation is, without a doubt, the [integrated circuit](/Integrated_circuit).  By packing multiple transistors onto a single silicon chip, engineers managed to shrink entire boards into something that could actually fit on a desk – provided your desk is the size of a small conference table and you’re willing to ignore the occasional whiff of burnt silicon.  This miniaturization also paved the way for the first true [microprocessor](/Microprocessor) concepts, though those would really take off a decade later.  

[Transistor](/Transistor) | [Silicon](/Silicon) | [Microprocessor](/Microprocessor)  

#### Memory and Storage  
Second‑generation machines finally got their hands on magnetic core memory, a technology that, while still bulky, was *far* more reliable than the chaotic punch‑card systems of yore.  The introduction of [magnetic drum memory](/Magnetic_drum_memory) and early [hard disk drives](/Hard_disk_drive) meant that data could be stored *persistently* – a concept that would later become the foundation of every modern data center’s existential crisis.  

[Hard disk drive](/Hard_disk_drive) | [Magnetic core memory](/Magnetic_core_memory)  

#### Input/Output Devices  
Gone were the days when the only way to talk to a computer was via a stack of paper tape or a set of cryptic punch cards.  The second generation introduced [keyboard](/Keyboard) input, [monitor](/Monitor) output, and even the occasional [mouse](/Mouse) (though the mouse would have to wait a few more years to become mainstream).  These peripheral devices made computing feel less like a ritual sacrifice and more like an actual conversation – albeit one where the computer still judged you silently.  

[Keyboard](/Keyboard) | [Monitor](/Monitor) | [Mouse](/Mouse)  

### Software Evolution  
#### Early Operating Systems  
With hardware finally stable enough to *not* explode on a regular basis, software developers could finally focus on creating something as complex as an [operating system](/Operating_system).  The first batch of OSes – such as IBM’s [OS/360](/OS/360) and DEC’s [TOPS‑10](/TOPS-10) – offered features like batch processing, multiprogramming, and, most importantly, the ability to *pretend* the machine was doing something useful while actually just waiting for you to type something.  

[Operating system](/Operating_system) | [Batch processing](/Batch_processing)  

#### Programming Languages  
The second generation also saw the birth of several high‑level [programming languages](/Programming_language) that attempted to make coding *less* like writing incantations in an ancient dead language.  Languages like [FORTRAN](/FORTRAN), [COBOL](/COBOL), and later [ALGOL](/ALGOL) gave programmers a modicum of readability, though they still required a degree of patience and an unhealthy amount of punctuation.  

[FORTRAN](/FORTRAN) | [COBOL](/COBOL) | [ALGOL](/ALGOL)  

